<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Case study</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the Chartered Institute of Environmental Health</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:14pt; font-weight:normal">1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:14pt">Executive</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:14pt"> Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">1.1</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The CIEH welcomes the Select Committee’s Inquiry into the Government’s review of housing standards and its proposals on the Code for Sustainable Homes.  The principal role for Environmental Health Practitioners is in the maintenance of housing standards and conditions in the private rented sector, but there is strong interest in the standards </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">et</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> for new build housing</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">, not least</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> as these are of course the private rented dwellings of the future. The consultation also raises important issues about accessibility and space standards</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">, which are of </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">particular</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> interest</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">1.2</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The key points of our submission are:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">On </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">accessibility</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">, the CIEH supports a move towards the Lifetime Homes standard </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">On </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">energy efficiency</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">, we argue for </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ret</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">tion of</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> the Code for Sustainable Homes </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">On </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">space standards</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">, we support a national minimum and do not see the need for a labelling approach as proposed by the Government.  We would like to see separate, h</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">igher standards on space retained for social housing.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Overall approach </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">2.1</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The consultation is concerned with the standards that are applied to new housing construction and seeks to both to simplify standards and remove unnecessary ones, concentrating on those that should be </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">mandatory</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">while other issues are left to be the subject of </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">voluntary </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">codes adopted by the industry. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">CIEH position</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">2.2</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The distinction between mandatory and voluntary is sensible, but the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">balance between the two has </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">to be set carefully. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">he housing market </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">currently favours the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">“seller” and voluntary codes cannot be relied on </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">alone </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">to achieve the housing stock required in the longer term. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Furthermore, government policies, especially its carbon-reduction targets, depend heavily on the performance of the current and future housing stock. The government should also be planning to ensure that the housing stock is better suited to the demographic shifts that are taking place. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Implementation </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">3.1</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">consultation </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">paper considers different methods for implementing the standards, e.g. embodying them in the Building Regulations. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">CIEH Position</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">3.2</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> CIEH ha</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">s </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">some concerns about placing sole reliance on the Building Regulations, firstly in terms of the consistency w</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">hen </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">applied on energy issues and secondly, while the</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">y</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> are a well-established and relatively stable mechanism, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">they have proven less successful in driving up </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">standards. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">3.3</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">It</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> i</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">s not only in energy efficiency that Building Reg</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ulations</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> are inconsistently applied</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">; t</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">hey</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> are</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> also not noted for</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> bringing about</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> step changes in standards</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> while the</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">re is resistance by</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> house builders </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> improvement</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">s.  But we do not view the solution as being in</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> voluntary codes</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Keeping the standards under review </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">CIEH Position </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">4.1</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Whilst this is n</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ot an issue of great significance for </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">the CIEH</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">we support the establishment of a </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">review group</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">, which</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> should </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">have a</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> broad</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> base </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">to reflect consumer and wider interests (e.g.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> on</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> environmental</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">accessibility</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> issues</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">) and should not be solely an industry forum</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">.  It </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">is not clear </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">to us </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">how this is different from the current B</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">uilding </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">egulations </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">dvisory </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ommittee</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> which </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">the CIEH </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ha</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> had occasional input into.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Standards for affordable housing </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">5.1</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Government proposes to remove separate standards for affordable housing but that its higher needs are ‘taken into account’ in implementation. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">CIEH Position </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">5.2</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">We agree with the Chartered Institute of Housing that s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">eparate standards for social housing have served the sector well. Of course, if the private sector w</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">as</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> willing/able to operate to the same standards then differences may no longer be justified, but recent experience suggests that it is not. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Accessibility </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">6.1</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Current standards</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> on accessibility</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> are in part M of the Building Regulations but there are also discretionary standards about wheelchair access and (particularly) the Lifetime Homes (LTH) standard</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">, while v</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">arious other standards are set by local authorities. The government proposes both a minimum, compulsory standard set in Building Regulations and two further optional levels – intermediate (similar to LTH) and high (fully wheelchair accessible) which could be applied to a proportion of units in a development. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">CIEH Position </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">6.2</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">For too long there ha</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> been ambiguity, not only in the standards to follow when designing accessible property but to the interpretation of the guidance given. The result of interpretation of the guidance alongside the often conflicting policies (also determining the building design) </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">have sometimes led</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">to “</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">hybrid</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">” properties</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> that </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> not always fit for purpose or which may have been over manufactured for ‘disability’, rather than being accessible.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">6.3</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Often when considering adaptations to a property the person requiring them has quite differing and individual needs. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Council Disabled Facilities Grant and adaptation </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">service</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> need to consider the individual anthropometrics; one size of adaptation does not always fit all.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">6.4</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">By making the policy clear and functional, it is hoped that ‘accessible and adaptable’ </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">homes will be provided </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">allow</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> for the easy tailoring to a person’s needs.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">6.5</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">It is very important to make the standards the same for private and affordable housing, which would hopefully open up the housing options for people perhaps affected by the welfare reform changes, or that are inadvertently discriminated against through lack of accessible stock across tenure. Encouraging private landlords to consider accessible stock might impact on the pressures on the council housing stock.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">6.6</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">‘The wheelchair standard’ should be researched and be more of a culmination of other recognised guidance. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">heelchair users</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> should be consulted in this research, which </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">should cover not only the internals of the building, but the approach, access and the provision of parking. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">6.7</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Some local authorities </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">have seen </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">increased demand </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">for one bed wheelchair accessible stock</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">, following</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> the introduction of the welfare reform changes, however, location of this also needs to be near community facilities or is not easily rented. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">There is some evidence also of</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> a rise in families requiring accessible, level access property, so that they are able to easily and independently tend to their children and stay together as a family in their chosen community. These are mostly 3-4 bed needs. Developers have reported that costs of building such stock are high due to the land required and there is no incentive to build this type of stock, resulting in costly extensions to</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">existing properties, if the building structure lends itself to this in the first place.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">6.8</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The part M requirements essentially make a home ‘</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">visitable</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">’ rather than fully useable overall by a disabled person.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> The debate is therefore essentially about whether LTH (or similar) should be required nationally across sectors.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> It already applies in London and several LAs outside London and the previous government planned to extend it to the private sector. The obvious arguments in favour are the ageing population and the much lower cost of incorporating higher standards from the outset. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">6.9</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Part M was a significant advance nevertheless it is somewhat tokenistic and can be applied that way. By contrast, LTHs are not only about the immobility of age and, for example, ought to facilitate caring for chronically sick people in the community.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">7</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Space </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">7.1</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">National space standards apply only in affordable housing through the HCA and GLA, although they may be enforced by LAs through planning policies. Given the variety of approaches there is obviously a case for harmonisation. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">7.2</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The government has backed away from directly tackling poor space standards and prefers a voluntary approach based on labelling.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> However, if the aim is to avoid conflicting approaches</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">, the Government </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">would </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">probably need to</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> rescind current planning guidance that encourages local standards, or else </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">encourage</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> a consistent voluntary standard which LAs would have to adopt if they wanted to </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">exceed</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> the minimum. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">CIEH Position </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">7.3</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">largely voluntary approach of the past clearly has</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">t delivered.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> Setting (adequate) mandatory standards would not only have significant practical benefits but be of symbolic importance in the government/construction industry relationship too.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">7.4</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Britain currently </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">has</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> the lowest floor space in new build in Europe and is the only country without minimum standards.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The CIEH </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">favour</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> a minimum standard that applies to all housing, not just affordable housing, that could then be consistently applied across England. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> We do not consider that an official labelling system is required above that.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">8</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Water efficiency </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">8.1</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">B</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">asic water efficiency is currently covered by the Building Regulations and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">local authorities</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> are able to put forward local standards, which are normally part of sustainability requirements linked to the Code. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The government favours continued standards and proposes a dual approach – one based on the whole house and the other on efficiency of individual fittings.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> The standards would be aimed at a similar level as currently. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">CIEH Position </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">8.2</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The CIEH is </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">sceptical of 'whole house' standards since these seem harder to enforce, lead to less market transformation and in some cases have encouraged the installation of inappropriate fittings (to 'balance' other inappropriate fittings) which are then replaced. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">We are also not convinced on the case for</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> more stringent local standards; it</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> i</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">s plain that household consumption cannot be squeezed inexorably to accommodate more and more incomers and where there</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> i</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">s no further scope for resource development or leakage reduction, the planning system has to say 'no'.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">9</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Energy </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">9.1</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">There are two main issues </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">of</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> concern </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">to the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">hartered Institute</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">: the proposed </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">wi</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">nding</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> up</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> of the Code for Sustainable Homes and the scrapping of the provisions in the Planning and Energy Act 2008 which permit local standards for energy efficiency to be set. The importance of the domestic sector in energy use and the double advantage of tackling energy-inefficiency in homes (i.e. both reducing energy us</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">e and cutting consumers’ costs)</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">means </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">it is vital that standards are as ambitious as possible if the government’s 2020 and 2050 carbon reduction targets are to be met. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">10</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Code for Sustainable Homes</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">CIEH Position</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">10.1</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> concerned at the loss of the Code for several reasons: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">While in theory its provisions can be incorporated elsewhere, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">we feel that </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">the Code has been a powerful tool in its own right and has established a standard which </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">many </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">have been proud to meet and publicize</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">he Code is not only about energy performance in the dwelling, but also takes account of wider issues such as the supply chain which could easily be forgotten and cannot easily be included in Building Regulations. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Compliance with the Code has been a key way to show how much higher eco-standards can be met and has created examples for the industry to follow. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">11</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Local standards </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">11.1</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Local planning authority standards have required developers to work to local sustainability goals, for example generating a proportion of energy on-site, from renewable sources.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">CIEH Position</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">11.2</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Initiatives like the "Merton Rule" </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">have worked well and</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> should be encouraged.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">An important consideration is that planners and planning authorities have often been in the driving seat for local sustainability ideas which have then been taken up more widely. </span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:14pt">---------------------------------------------------------------------------------</span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:14pt">The Chartered Institute of Environmental Health</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">As a </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">professional body</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">, we set standards and accredit courses and qualifications for the education of our professional members and other environmental health practitioners.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">As a </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">knowledge centre</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">, we provide information, evidence and policy advice to local and national government, environmental and public health practitioners, industry and other stakeholders.  We publish books and magazines; run educational events and commission research.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">As an </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">awarding body</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">, we provide qualifications, events, and trainer and candidate support materials on topics relevant to health, wellbeing and safety to develop workplace skills and best practice in volunteers, employees, business managers and business owners.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">As a </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">campaigning organisation</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">we work to push environmental health further up the public agenda and to promote improvements in environmental and public health policy.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">We are a </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">registered charity</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> with over 10,500 members across England, Wales and Northern Ireland.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">3</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt">5</span></p></div></body></html>